ğŸ”‘ When does Greedy work?

Greedy works ONLY when the problem has this property:

Choosing the best option now will NOT spoil the final answer.

If wrong choice now canâ€™t be fixed later âŒ â†’ Greedy fails
If wrong choice never happens âœ”ï¸ â†’ Greedy works

## WHEN GREEDY FAILS 
Step 2ï¸âƒ£: Convert the problem so GREEDY FAILS
âŒ Change the coin set

Letâ€™s change it to:

{1, 3, 4}


âš ï¸ Only this change is enough
Problem statement remains SAME:

Given infinite supply of coins {1, 3, 4}, find minimum number of coins for n.

Step 3ï¸âƒ£: Show GREEDY FAILING (Very important)
Take n = 6
Greedy thinking (wrong)
Take 4 â†’ remaining 2
Take 1 â†’ remaining 1
Take 1 â†’ remaining 0
Total coins = 3

Optimal solution (better)
3 + 3 = 6
Total coins = 2


âŒ Greedy failed
âœ”ï¸ Optimal used fewer coins

Step 4ï¸âƒ£: WHY greedy failed here (Key intuition)

Because:

Coin 4 looks attractive locally

But 3 + 3 is globally better

ğŸ“Œ Greedy got trapped by a local optimum

Step 5ï¸âƒ£: Write this as an EXAM ANSWER

You can write ğŸ‘‡

If the coin denominations are {1, 3, 4}, greedy strategy fails.
For n = 6, greedy picks 4 first and uses 3 coins (4,1,1), whereas optimal solution uses only 2 coins (3,3).
Hence greedy does not guarantee optimal solution for all coin systems.

Step 6ï¸âƒ£: General Rule to Detect Greedy FAILURE

Greedy fails when:

A larger coin blocks a better combination

Medium coins together beat a large coin

ğŸ”‘ One-line rule (remember this forever)

If a coin is NOT a good replacement of smaller coins, greedy may fail.

Step 7ï¸âƒ£: Another greedy-failing example

Coin set:

{1, 5, 6, 9}


n = 11

Greedy:

9 + 1 + 1 = 3 coins


Optimal:

5 + 6 = 2 coins


âŒ Greedy fails again

ğŸ”¥ SUPER IMPORTANT EXAM LINE

Greedy algorithm works for canonical coin systems (like Indian currency), but fails for arbitrary denominations.

(ğŸ’¯ teacher-impression line)

